The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 Good Morning

 Hello It's Wednesday, September 29, 2004

 Road to avoid

 Deshapran Sashmal Road. One flank closed to lay water pipeline.

 On stage

 Crossword and Spandan will present Her Stories (based on Vagina Monologues by Eve Ansler) directed by Sujoy Prosad Chatterjee, at Crossword, 6.45 pm. Cast includes Anindita Sarbadhicari, Renu Roy, Sudeshna Roy, Poonam Singh, Alokananda Roy and Deboleena Dutta. 

 Launch

 The Oxford Companion to Indian Theatre, edited by Ananda Lal, will be launched at British Council, 7 pm. A panel discussion, featuring Lokendra Arambam, Mahesh Dattani, Usha Ganguly, Anjum Katyal, Devajit Bandyopadhyay and Ananda Lal, will follow.

 Terror Sans Frontiers by Jaideep Saikia will be released at Oxford Bookstore, 6.30 pm. 

 Soiree

 Hindustani classical music recital by Vinayak Sumant Chittar (sitar) and Md. Aslam Khan (tabla) at the ITC Sangeet Research Academy, 6 pm. 

 Plant fair

 Plant Mela 2004 is on at Agri-Horticultural Society of India, 7 am to 7 pm.

 Art watch

 Ethnic artefacts, jewellery and garments on display at CIMA Gallery, 11 am to 8 pm.

 Paintings on view at names-AN.art on Rashbehari Avenue.




